WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.600
Do you work with databases but want to use the power of dplyr with functions like mutate and the pipe?

00:00:05.600 --> 00:00:10.000
Look no further than dbplyr, the database backend for dplyr.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:15.000
dbplyr is designed to work with database tables as if they were local data frames,

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:18.200
and it automatically converts dplyr code to SQL.

00:00:18.200 --> 00:00:22.200
For example, let's load our packages, next connect to the database,

00:00:22.200 --> 00:00:25.000
then run our query using just dplyr code.

00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:29.000
Notice that there is the pipe, groupby, arrange, summarize.

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:31.600
But if you were to run the showQuery function,

00:00:31.600 --> 00:00:34.599
you'll actually see the SQL that is running in the backend,

00:00:34.599 --> 00:00:37.000
so you don't have to leave the comfort of R.

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:40.599
And if you prefer Python, Ibis has similar functionality.

00:00:40.599 --> 00:00:43.599
It can also run on top of SQL backends,

00:00:43.599 --> 00:00:46.000
and kind of looks a little bit like dplyr.

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:48.400
What tool are you interested in learning about next?

00:00:48.400 --> 00:00:49.599
Let us know in the comments.

